ANTHRAX - AUSTRALIA (03): (NEW SOUTH WALES) PRIOR OUTBREAKS IN 2012
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 19 Mar 2013
From: Barbara Moloney <barbara.moloney@dpi.nsw.gov.au> [edited]


The most recent previous bovine cases in NSW were on single properties in each of the Condobolin (1 death) and Molong (3 deaths) districts in December 2012. These have been reported in the Animal Health Surveillance Quarterly; 17(4) -- in press). The previous bovine case (1 death) before that was in 2009 as reported in ProMED-mail.

The occurrence of anthrax in cattle as compared to sheep is of no particular significance in the Australian context. The species affected is simply determined by the stock being run on the affected property.

The properties affected in the current incident are within the so-called historical 'anthrax belt' where the disease is not unexpected. In Australia, there is no epidemiological evidence to suggest a role for horse flies in transmission of anthrax.

--
